\begin{equation*}{\mathrm{{\zeta}}}_{ge}=\frac{{v- \left \left({\mathrm{{\mu}}}_{p}+{\mathrm{{\mu}}}_{c}\right) \right }/{2}}{{ \left \left({\mathrm{{\sigma}}}_{p}+{\mathrm{{\sigma}}}_{c}\right) \right }/{2}}\end{equation*}\end{document}where μP and σP are respectively the mean and SD computed from the gene expression values for that gene in the phenotype group, and μc and σc are their corresponding values computed from the control group (Eq. 1). The value of this function is then plotted using a pseudocolor map that represents ζge = 0 as black, ζge > 0 as progressively brighter hues of red, and ζge < 0 as progressively brighter levels of green. ζge = 4 and ζge = −4 correspond to complete saturation of the red and the green, respectively. The resulting pseudocolor map associates the same colors to measurements that are off by the same number of SDs from their expected value.

